	<text>
		<body>
			<p>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_klein_marta">Marta Klein</persName> Testimony (doc. 301/12) </p>
			<p>Original, manuscript, 2 pages, 150 x 210 mm, Polish language</p>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010012_01.jpg"/>
			<p>We were in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/593116/vilnius.html">Wilno</placeName> when the Russo-<term type="subject"
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159">German</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term> broke out. Right after the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject">Germans</term> entered, because it was <date
					when="1941-06-12">July 12, [19]41</date>, I mysteriously lost my husband. He went out for a few cigarettes and he never returned.
				As I found out [later], he was caught by the <orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName>
				and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-636" type="subject">kidnapped</term> in a car. That same day, three
				thousand Jews were taken that way. I was left with my 15-year-old son. I <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hid</term> him and guarded him like my own life, and
				we managed to survive the many purges, and that was no mean feat, for when the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject">ghetto</term> had existed for three months, only
				12,000 Jews were left of a total of 75,000. Fearing that the time would come for those who remain as well, we <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-204" type="subject">escaped</term> to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/776069/bialystok.html">Białystok</placeName>. That is where the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">slaughter</term> began on <date when="1943-02-05"
					>February 5, [19]43</date>. The first time, twelve thousand people were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-518" type="subject">deported</term> to <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2032" type="camp">Treblinka</placeName>, and 1100 were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">killed</term> on the spot. After a pause of a
				half-year, the total liquidation of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-545" type="subject"
					>ghetto</term> began. That was <date when="1943-08-16">August 16, 1943</date>. I <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject">hid</term> with my siblings in an attic <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">shelter</term>. At day break and evening [?], we
				crawled to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">shelter</term>, cooking a meager
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">meal</term> at night, our <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">food</term> consisted of some groats and a few <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832">biscuits</term> without any fat at all. <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">My brother and his wife</term> got out after 4 weeks,
				we didn’t have anywhere to go to. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject"
					>conditions</term> were worse and worse, the water was turned off, we couldn’t cook and to make matters worse, we often witnessed
				the discovery of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">shelters</term> in the
				neighborhood. The people who were discovered were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject"
					>killed</term> mercilessly, even the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-515" type="subject"
					>corpses</term> were abused: <note type="gloss">Diese elenden hunde (German) – These pathetic dogs.</note> and homeric laughter
				was their final farewell. We suffered like that for nine weeks. We felt that we wouldn’t be able to hold out anymore. My <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">son</term> decided to risk going out, since we were
				near the end anyway. One evening, he dug a hole under the exit gate and made it out successfully. He went to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">relatives</term> that were set up with some <term
					type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_poles">Poles</term> and my <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">sister-in-law</term> managed <pb n="2"
					facs="EHRI-ET-ZIH3010012_02.jpg"/> to find a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-262" type="subject"
					>hiding place</term>. We had to leave there after just fourteen days, however, because the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">child</term> told the neighbors about us. Wandering
				the streets, we approached a passerby, who turned out to be a merciful person, took us under his wing and found us a good <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-265" type="subject">shelter</term>. We took it easy for three months.
				During that time, several <term type="subject" ref="#ehri_et_nationalities_belarusians">Belarusians</term> were appointed to our
				apartment, and we were once again without a roof over our heads. My <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837"
					type="subject">son</term> went to Mr. <persName ref="#ehri_et_czulinski">Czuliński</persName> again, which is what our benefactor
				was called, and he promised to find us such a place again. And after a few days, he really did tell us that his former maid proposed a
				place with her. He and my <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">son</term> went to agree
				on the conditions, and they never came back home. As we learned later, she was a cook for the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName> and was in their service. They were taken in
				handcuffs on <date when="1944-01-27">January 27, 1944</date>, to the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-350">Gestapo</orgName>, and from there to <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-669" type="subject">prison</term>. <persName ref="#ehri_et_czulinski"
					>Czuliński</persName> was sent to a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term>,
				to <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3099434/gdansk.html">Gdańsk</placeName>. He was the one who sent word that it had been the
				maid who delivered them into the hands of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject"
					>executioners</term>. My poor <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-824" type="subject">child</term>
				stayed in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-669" type="subject">death cell</term> suffering and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">hungry</term> until the next <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term> to <placeName
					ref="http://www.geonames.org/753287/zielona.html">Zielona,</placeName> where the martyrs were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-541" type="subject">killed</term> during that period. My <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject">relatives</term> took me under their care and
				convinced their protectors to keep and protect me as well. We were there when the <orgName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-004583">Red Army</orgName> arrived and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-573" type="subject">liberated</term> us. It is only now that I feel the
				full brunt of my misfortune, all the delusions and hopes have burst. No one will return to us our dear ones who are <term
					type="subject" ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745">dead</term> now, who were <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">killed</term> in such a brutal fashion.</p>
			<p><placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/776069/bialystok.html">Białystok</placeName>, <date when="1944-09-01">September 1,
				1944</date>.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_klein_marta">Marta Klein</persName></p>
